      "Reconstruction and rebuilding of damaged structures"
    ],
    "summary": "On April 17, 2013, at approximately 7:51 pm CDT, a fire and explosion occurred at the West Fertilizer Company facility in West, Texas. The facility stored between 40 and 60 tons of fertilizer grade ammonium nitrate (FGAN). The explosion fatally injured 12 emergency responders and 3 members of the public, with more than 260 injured. The blast destroyed the WFC facility and caused widespread damage to over 150 offsite buildings, including schools, a nursing home, and residential structures. Total insurance-related losses were estimated at approximately $230 million.",
    "recommendations": [
      "Implement inherently safer technology and alternative FGAN formulations",
      "Establish automatic sprinkler systems in FGAN storage facilities",
      "Improve federal and state regulations for FGAN storage and handling",
      "Enhance emergency response training and pre-incident planning for hazardous materials",
      "Implement land use planning and zoning regulations to separate hazardous chemical storage from populated areas",
      "Improve insurance coverage requirements and loss control inspections",
      "Enhance firefighter training on FGAN hazards and appropriate response procedures"
    ],
    "key_phrases": [
      "fertilizer grade ammonium nitrate detonation",
      "contamination of FGAN pile",
      "lack of automatic sprinkler system",
